stat%20called%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fvo2-max-explained-what-is-good-how-improve-2024-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EVO2%20max%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ECommonly%20used%20as%20a%20marker%20of%20endurance%2C%20a%20higher%20VO2%20max%20means%20your%20lungs%20are%20better%20at%20taking%20in%20oxygen%20with%20each%20breath%20and%20your%20heart%20is%20better%20at%20pumping%20oxygenated%20blood%20throughout%20your%20body.%20So%2C%20in%20the%20end%2C%20you're%20getting%20more%20oxygen%20to%20your%20muscles%20for%20energy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAn%20average%2C%20healthy%20adult%20under%2045%20might%20have%20a%20VO2%20max%20of%20around%2035%20to%2042%20mL%2Fkg%2Fmin%20%E2%80%94%20that's%20written%20in%20milliliters%20of%20oxygen%20consumed%20per%20minute%20per%20kilogram%20of%20body%20weight.%20But%20regular%20exercise%20can%20help%20boost%20VO2%20max.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat's%20why%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Eelite%20endurance%20athletes%2C%20including%20Olympians%2C%20in%20sports%20like%20rowing%2C%20running%2C%20cycling%2C%20and%20triathlon%20can%20have%20a%20much%20higher%20VO2%20max%20in%20the%2060s%2C%2070s%2C%20and%20beyond.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20Winter%20Games%2C%20cross-country%20skiers%20have%20exceptional%20VO2%20max%20measures%2C%20with%20one%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2F25611016%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E2015%20study%3C%2Fa%3E%20finding%20that%20Olympic%20medalists'%20scores%20ranged%20between%2067%20to%2084%20mL%2Fkg%2Fmin%2C%20on%20average.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20may%20sound%20out%20of%20reach%2C%20but%20there%20are%20ways%20to%20increase%20your%20own%20VO2%20max%2C%20even%20if%20you're%20not%20an%20Olympian.%20For%20example%2C%20the%20%26quot%3Bsweet%20spot%26quot%3B%20for%20maximizing%20fitness%20benefits%20is%20typically%20by%20combining%20different%20exercise%20intensities%20with%20%3Cspan%3Earound%2080%25%20easy%20and%2020%25%20hard.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EThe%20insides%20of%20their%20mitochondria%20are%20more%20wrinkly.%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Close%20up%20image%20of%20mitochondria%20in%20a%20cell%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F66b264eab4912df3ae19444a%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221500%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3E%3Cp%3EGetty%20Images%3B%20Natalie%20Ammari%2FBI%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EOlympians%20can%20even%20look%20different%20on%20a%20microscopic%20level.%20For%20example%2C%20let's%20zoom%20into%20the%20powerhouse%20of%20the%20cell.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMitochondria%20are%20bean-shaped%20organelles%20that%20produce%20energy%20for%20almost%20every%20cell%20in%20the%20body.%20Specifically%2C%20they%20turn%20sugars%2C%20fats%2C%20or%20proteins%20into%20ATP%20%E2%80%94%20units%20of%20energy%20that%20the%20muscles%20then%20use%20to%20contract.%20They're%20kind%20of%20a%20big%20deal.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERegular%2C%20sustained%20exercise%20can%20increase%20the%20number%20of%20mitochondria%20in%20your%20muscles.%20The%20studies%20on%20that%20are%20%26quot%3Bpretty%20conclusive%2C%26quot%3B%20according%20to%20Dr.%20Hilary%20Vernon%2C%20the%20director%20of%20the%20Mitochondrial%20Care%20Center%20at%20the%20Johns%20Hopkins%20Hospital.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20a%20few%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fphysoc.onlinelibrary.wiley.com%2Fdoi%2F10.1113%2FJP284394%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erecent%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fphysoc.onlinelibrary.wiley.com%2Fdoi%2Fepdf%2F10.1113%2FJP273040%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Estudies%3C%2Fa%3E%20suggest%20that%20athleticism%20also%20does%20your%20cells%20an%20even%20sneakier%20favor%2C%20by%20increasing%20the%20number%20of%20folds%20along%20the%20mitochondria's%20inner%20membrane.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThis%20is%20thought%20to%20be%20important%20because%20that%20increases%20the%20surface%20area%20of%20those%20folds%20and%20increases%20the%20amount%20of%20energy%20that%20can%20be%20produced%2C%26quot%3B%20Dr.%20Vernon%20told%20BI.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBasically%2C%20exercise%20might%20condition%20your%20mitochondria%20to%20better%20fuel%20future%20exercise.%20%26quot%3BThe%20more%20ATP%20you%20can%20produce%2C%20ostensibly%2C%20the%20more%20force%20you%20can%20produce%20on%20muscle%20and%20the%20more%20repetition%20you%20can%20produce%20on%20muscle%2C%26quot%3B%20Vernon%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20world's%20top%20athletes%20are%20likely%20maximizing%20this%20cellular%20benefit.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3ERegular%20exercise%20changes%20Olympians'%20gut%20microbiome.%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Image%20of%20intestines%20in%20human%20body%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F66b265b1393cd3c8629ba93f%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221500%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3E%3Cp%3EGetty%20Images%3B%20Natalie%20Ammari%2FBI%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EExercise%20has%20an%20interesting%20effect%20on%20the%20gut%20microbiome%2C%20suggesting%20that%20the%20types%20and%20amount%20of%20microorganisms%20in%20Olympians'%20GI%20tracts%20probably%20look%20different%20from%20the%20average%20person's.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EExercise%20generates%20small%20molecules%20called%20metabolites%2C%20some%20of%20which%20can%20improve%20muscle%20strength%20and%20endurance%2C%20helping%20athletes%20work%20out%20for%20longer.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2F34152092%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EPreliminary%20research%3C%2Fa%3E%20has%20found%20that%20different%20exercises%20can%20produce%20different%20types%20and%20amounts%20of%20metabolites.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20the%20ways%20that%20exercise%20changes%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwoman-couldnt-lose-weight-missing-crucial-gut-microbes-2024-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egut%20microbiomes%3C%2Fa%3E%20aren't%20fully%2