om%2Fpersonal-finance%2Finvesting%2Fhow-to-find-financial-advisor%5C%22%3Efinancial%20planner%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%94%20here%20are%20the%20big%20mistakes%20I%20see%20often%20and%20how%20to%20avoid%20them%20yourself.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E1.%20Skipping%20out%20on%20(or%20delaying)%20saving%20aggressively%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ENot%20saving%20enough%20is%20the%20biggest%20financial%20mistake%20almost%20everyone%20makes%2C%20regardless%20of%20their%20specific%20goals.%20If%20you%20want%20to%20retire%20early%2C%20maintaining%20an%20aggressive%20savings%20rate%20during%20your%20working%20years%20is%20a%20requirement%20for%20achieving%20that%20goal.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAt%20my%20financial%20planning%20firm%2C%20we%20recommend%20most%20of%20our%20clients%20invest%20a%20minimum%20of%2025%25%20of%20their%20gross%20household%20income%20a%20year%20in%20long-term%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Finvesting%5C%22%3Einvestments%3C%2Fa%3E.%20But%20for%20those%20who%20want%20to%20retire%20in%20their%2050s%2C%20that%20recommendation%20rises%20to%2030%25%20to%2050%25%20of%20their%20income.%20Retiring%20pre-50%20likely%20won't%20happen%20unless%20you%20put%20away%20well%20over%20half%20of%20your%20income%20between%20now%20and%20then.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhat%20to%20do%20instead%3A%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20Prioritize%20your%20savings.%20Treat%20it%20like%20a%20non-negotiable%20expense%2C%20then%20automate%20it%20to%20ensure%20a%20portion%20of%20your%20income%20goes%20directly%20and%20immediately%20into%20your%20retirement%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Finvesting%2Fbest-investment-apps-for-beginners%5C%22%3Einvestment%20accounts%3C%2Fa%3E%20when%20you%20get%20paid.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E2.%20Saving%20your%20money%20but%20forgetting%20to%20invest%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWe%20once%20had%20a%20client%20come%20to%20us%20with%20hundreds%20of%20thousands%20in%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Finvesting%2Fwhat-is-401k%5C%22%3E401(k)%3C%2Fa%3E%20...%20and%20almost%20all%20of%20it%20was%20sitting%20in%20cash.%20It%20was%20an%20impressive%20amount%20of%20savings%20%E2%80%94%20and%20a%20horrifying%20opportunity%20cost.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat%20money%20spent%20years%20sitting%20on%20the%20sidelines%20rather%20than%20being%20invested%20in%20the%20market%20with%20the%20ability%20to%20compound%20over%20time.%20Letting%20cash%20sit%20in%20your%20portfolio%20creates%20cash%20drag%2C%20which%20reduces%20your%20overall%20returns.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EYou%20can%20also%20have%20too%20much%20cash%20sitting%20around%20in%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbanking%2Fbest-banks%5C%22%3Ebank%20account%3C%2Fa%3E.%20While%20you%20absolutely%20should%20have%20a%20cash%20reserve%20for%20emergencies%2C%20you%20shouldn't%20keep%20more%20in%20an%20emergency%20fund%20than%20you%20actually%20need%20on%20hand%2C%20as%20you'll%20miss%20critical%20opportunities%20for%20growth.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhat%20to%20do%20instead%3A%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20Assess%20your%20cash%20needs%20and%20invest%20any%20excess%20in%20a%20globally%20diversified%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Finvesting%2Finvestment-portfolio%5C%22%3Eportfolio%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20long-term%20growth.%20If%20you%20want%20to%20retire%20early%2C%20you%20need%20every%20available%20dollar%20working%20to%20earn%20%3Cem%3Emore%3C%2Fem%3E%20dollars.%20Periodically%20review%20your%20portfolio%20and%20eliminate%20cash%20drag.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E3.%20Failing%20to%20diversify%20investment%20account%20types%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EYour%20current%20401(k)%20can%20help%20you%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fbeyondyourhammock.com%2F51-2%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ebuild%20up%20the%20savings%3C%2Fa%3E%20you%20need%20to%20retire%2C%20but%C2%A0if%20you%20want%20to%20retire%20%3Cem%3Eearly%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20you%20may%20not%20be%20able%20to%20access%20that%20money%20without%20incurring%20penalties%20and%20taxes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20are%20workarounds%2C%20but%20the%20general%20rule%20is%20that%20you%20cannot%20access%20money%20in%20qualified%20retirement%20accounts%20before%20age%2059%C2%BD.%20If%20you%20retire%20at%2050%2C%20that's%20nearly%2010%20years%20of%20your%20life%20that%20you%20need%20to%20fund%20from%20other%20sources.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EJust%20like%20too%20much%20concentration%20in%20a%20particular%20asset%20within%20an%20investment%20portfolio%20can%20create%20unnecessary%20volatility%20and%20expose%20you%20to%20more%20downside%20risk%2C%20relying%20on%20a%20single%20type%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Finvesting%2Fbest-retirement-plans%5C%22%3Eretirement%20account%3C%2Fa%3E%20can%20limit%20your%20financial%20flexibility%20in%20the%20future.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhat%20to%20do%20instead%3A%20%3C%2Fstrong%3EWork%20toward%20your%20early%20retirement%20goal%20by%20deploying%20a%20mix%20of%20tax-deferred%2C%20after-tax%2C%20and%20taxable%20accounts.%20By%20saving%20into%20a%20variety%20of%20vehicles%2C%20you%20create%20more%20options%20for%20funding%20lifestyle%20regardless%20of%20your%20age%20when%20you%20choose%20to%20retire%2C%20and%20you%20also%20give%20yourself%20the%20ability%20to%20manage%20your%20tax%20liabilities%20more%20effectively.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E4.%20Relying%20too%20heavily%20on%20your%20employer's%20benefits%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20your%20plan%20only%20works%20so%20long%20as%20you%20stay%20at%20a%20certain%20employer%2C%20making%20a%20specific%20income%20for%20a%20defined%20number%20of%20years%2C%20it's%20risky.%20So%20much%20depends%20on%20factors%20outside%20your%20control.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESimilarly%2C%20if%20you%20need%20to%20receive%20a%20particular%20amount%20and%20kind%20of%20compensation%20(like%20equity%2C%20deferred%20comp%2C%20or%20a%20pension)%2C%20it%20might%20be%20ha